# What is a do-while Loop?

A **do-while loop** is a control statement that executes a block of code at least once because the condition is checked after the loop body executes.

---

# Why Use a do-while Loop?

Use a do-while loop when the code must execute **at least once**, regardless of whether the condition is initially true or false.

Common uses:

- ATM menus
- Calculator menus
- Game menus
- Input validation
- Retry operations

---

# Syntax

```java
do{

    // statements

}while(condition);
```

> **Note:** A semicolon (`;`) is required after the `while(condition)`.

---

# Flow of Execution

```
Execute Loop Body

↓

Check Condition

↓

True?

↓

Repeat

↓

False?

↓

Exit Loop
```

---

# Example

```java
int i = 1;

do{
    System.out.println(i);
    i++;
}while(i <= 5);
```

Output

```
1
2
3
4
5
```

---

# while vs do-while

| while | do-while |
|--------|-----------|
| Entry-controlled | Exit-controlled |
| Condition checked first | Condition checked after the loop body |
| May execute zero times | Executes at least once |

---

# Infinite do-while Loop

```java
do{
    System.out.println("Hello");
}while(true);
```

This loop never terminates unless interrupted.

---

# Time Complexity

```java
do{
    i++;
}while(i <= n);
```

Time Complexity

```
O(n)
```

---

```java
do{
    i++;
}while(i <= 100);
```

Time Complexity

```
O(1)
```

